e Land of Israel -- t19 Karaite Ritual -- t20 Living Judaism in Confucian Culture: Being Jewish and Being Chinese -- tArt and Aesthetics -- t21 Defending, Enjoying, and Regulating the Visual -- t22 Illustrating History and Illuminating Identity in the Art of the Passover Haggadah -- t23 The Arts of Calligraphy and Composition, and the Love of Books -- t24 Jewish Preaching in Fifteenth-Century Spain -- tMagic and Mysticism -- t25 The Book of the Great Name -- t26 Visionary Experiences among Spanish Crypto-Jewish Women -- t27 Mystical Eating and Food Practices in the Zohar -- t28 Devotional Rites in a Sufi Mode -- t29 Pietistic Customs from Safed -- t30 Jewish Exorcism: Early Modern Traditions and Transformations -- t31 Rabbi Menahem Nahum of Chernobyl: Personal Practices of a Hasidic Master -- tRemarkable Lives -- t32 The Life of Moses ben Maimon -- t33 Dolce of Worms: The Lives and Deaths of an Exemplary Medieval Jewish Woman and Her Daughters -- t34 The Earliest Hebrew First-Crusade Narrative -- t35 Leon Modena's Autobiography -- t36 The Early Messianic Career of Shabbatai Zvi -- t37 The Life of Glikl of Hameln -- t38 Israel ben Eliezer, the Baal Shem Tov -- t39 The Scholarly Life of the Gaon of Vilna -- tAPPENDIX The Jewish Festivals -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection of original materials provides a sweeping view of medieval and early modern Jewish ritual and religious practice. Including such diverse texts as ritual manuals, legal codes, mystical books, autobiographical writings, folk literature, and liturgical poetry, it testifies to the enormous variety of practices that characterized Judaism in the twelve hundred years between 600 and 1800 C.E. Its focus on religious practice and experience--how Judaism was actually lived by people from day to day--makes this anthology unique among the few sourcebooks available. The volume encompasses the broad scope and complex texture of Jewish religious practice, taking into account many aspects of Jewish culture that have hitherto been relatively neglected: the religious life of ordinary people, the role and status of women, art and aesthetics, and marginalized as well as remote Jewish communities. It introduces such remarkable personalities as Moses Maimonides, Leon Modena, and Gluckel of Hameln, and presents extraordinary texts on festival practice, Torah study, mystical communities, meditation, exorcism, the practice of charity, and folk rites marking birth and death. Representing state-of-the-art scholarship by distinguished academics from around the world, the volume includes many materials never before translated into English. Each text is preceded by an accessible introduction, making this book suitable for college and university students as well as a general audience. Whether read as a deliberate course of study or dipped into selectively for a glimpse into fascinating Jewish lives and places, Judaism in Practice holds rich rewards for any reader.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aJewsvBiography. 0aJudaismvWorks to 1900. 0aJudaismxCustoms and practicesxHistoryvSources. 0aJudaismxHistoryyMedieval and early modern period, 425-1789vSources. 0aJudaismxHistoryyMedieval and early modern period, 425-1789. 0aWomen in JudaismxHistoryvSources. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aAaron ben Jacob ha-Kohen.  aAbrahams, Israel.  aAbravanel, Benvenida.  aAdderet Eliyahu (Bashyachi).  aAdelman, Howard.  aBaruch of Arezzo.  aBashyachi, Elijah.  aBasola, Moses.  aBook of Jubilees.  aBuddhism.  aCharlemagne.  aConfucianism.  aConservative Judaism.  aDaggers of Faith (Chazan).  aDolce of Worms.  aEcstatic Religion (Lewis).  aElbogen, Ismar.  aFalashas.  aGao N